<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Quercus vacciniifolia </i>is a long-lived, evergreen shrub that grows to 1.5 m in height. Leaves are oblong, mostly entire to low serrate, and glabrous. Shrubs produce large acorn crops at irregular intervals. Seeds germinate without stratification. Small animals cache the acorns, which other wildlife eat also. Plants sprout from swollen root crowns after damage to their trunks. Species also reproduces by layering (Howard 1992m).The shrubs act as nurse plants, moderating environmental conditions and offering seedlings protection. Shrubs are moderately shade tolerant (Nixon and Muller 1997). <br/>
<br/>
<i>Quercus vacciniifolia </i>hybridizes with <i>Q. chrysolepis </i>at lower montane elevations (Nixon 2002). The hybrid is shrubby. Leaves are similar to those of both parents, and the stems and twigs are thick and stiff as in <i>Q. chrysolepis</i>. In contrast, the stems and twigs are thin and pliable in <i>Q. vacciniifolia, </i>allowing them to bend easily under heavy winter snow loads; it is easy to walk through stands of <i>Q. vacciniifolia</i>. <br/>
<br/>
This is one of the most common of the montane chaparral types from lower montane to subalpine elevations in the central and northern Sierra Nevada and the Klamath Mountains. It frequently occupies glacially scoured landscapes, where it may occur in patchy stands on thin soil over bedrock. <i>Q. vacciniifolia </i>occurs on a variety of substrates, especially granitic, mafic, and ultramafic ones. These conditions can restrict the conifer growth. Individuals of <i>Q. vacciniifolia </i>also occur in the other montane chaparral types, as a dominant in open forest understories, and as scattered shrubs in dense forests. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
