<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Fire Characteristics</h4>
	<div class="text"><i>Quercus vacciniifolia </i>sprouts from the root crown after fire. It has resinous, flammable leaves, an unusual character for an oak. Its low, spreading growth form encourages surface fire in open forest stands, where it acts as a ladder fuel (Howard 1992m). In burned forested sites, <i>Q. vacciniifolia </i>may dominate for 10-50 years until conifers establish and overtop the shrubs. It also persists as a montane chaparral type on a variety of rocky sites with shallow soils. <i>Arctostaphylos nevadensis </i>is the typical associate (Fites-Kaufman et al. 2007).</div>
	<table class="zebraStripe">
		
		<tr>
			<td class="key">Fire return interval</td>
			<td>Medium (25-75+ years)
				
