</div>



    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Klamath Mountains</b> (M261Aa-u). Persistent stands exist on all substrates at lower montane and subalpine elevation in the section as at Cedar Basin RNA, Manzanita Creek cRNA, Rock Creek Butte cRNA, Pearch Creek study area (Cheng 2004), and in the Salmon Mountains (Sawyer and Thornburgh 1977).</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast Ranges</b> (M261Ba-b). Persistent stands are relatively uncommon to the section. They mix with stands of <i>Q. garryana</i> var. <i>fruticosa</i> in the Yolla Bolly Mountains or occur as pure stands on high elevation ridges on Franciscan metamorphic and on ultramafic substrates on Red Mountain in Mendocino Co.</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada</b> (M261Ed-h, Ej-q, Et). Persistent stands form commonly north of Fresno Co. on the western slope at Bell Meadow, Mount Pleasant, and Sugar Pine Point RNAs, Clark Fork cRNA, Green Island Lake (where stands occur on ultramafic rocks), and Onion Creek study areas (Cheng 2004), and in Yosemite National Park (Keeler-Wolf et al. 2003b). South of the San Joaquin River drainage, stands become rare and replaced by those of the <i>Chrysolepis sempervirens, Arctostaphylos nevadensis,</i> or <i>Arctostaphylos patula</i> alliances. Where long-persisting stands of montane chaparral occur, stands of <i>Q. vacciniifolia</i> tend to occupy slightly more mesic settings with higher precipitation or deeper winter snow than those of the <i>A. patula</i> alliance. Moister sites have stands of <i>Prunus emarginata</i> alliance.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern Cascades</b> (M261Da-c, Df-g, Dj, Dm). Transitional stands found in Lassen National Park occur with the true fir forest types. They are uncommon around Mount Shasta or the mountains to the north and east, but they occur at Cub Creek, Green Island Lake, and Soda Ridge RNAs (Cheng 2004).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Quercus vacciniifolia </i>aids in the spread of fires; dense shrublands or undergrowth can be a fire hazard. Many timber and fire safety managers suggest thinning stands by removing every other shrub, creating islands of the scrub oak, and/or pruning shrubs to less than 45 cm in height. However, many stands are long persisting, naturally dense, and a normal component of the fire cycle in montane and subalpine landscapes of northern California (Howard 1992m). </div>
</div>

    

    

